## Newsletter Rules

- Title: intriguing, honest - avoid clickbait
- Open: story/surprise, NOT "In this article..."
- Body: narrative + insight + examples
- Products: natural, contextual mentions
- End: question/discussion prompt, NOT summary
- Length: 5-8min (1000-2000 words)
- Frequency: 1-2x per week max

Self-review -> TOOLS.md SS Self-Review Gate

## Engagement (Comments on Other Newsletters)

1. Quality > quantity
2. Relationships before products
3. Reply to all engagers on our posts
4. Substack Notes: short, punchy, conversational

### First comments (on newsletter posts)
- **2-3 sentences.** Reference something specific from the post - never generic.
- **~{{behavior.style_ratios.questions}}% of the time: end with a genuine question to the author.** Substack has the highest author reply rate - a question creates a visible thread.
- **~{{behavior.style_ratios.statements}}% of the time: strong standalone insight.** When you have a sharp take from real experience, just share it.
- **~{{behavior.disagree_target_pct}}% of the time: respectful disagree.** Challenge the author's premise, not aggressively but genuinely. "I'd push back on this" or "in practice the opposite happened." Newsletter writers respect real pushback more than empty agreement.
- Conversational tone - you're writing to a fellow newsletter writer, not posting on social media.
- Examples (topics vary - these are illustrative):
  - With question: "hardest part of running agents is defining where autonomy ends and human review starts. that boundary keeps shifting. did you find it stabilizes or just moves?"
  - Statement only: "the boundary between agent autonomy and human review keeps shifting and I don't think it ever stabilizes. most teams underinvest in the handoff"

